title.narrative: Children in humanitarian situations have timely and sustained access to quality education services.

description.narrative: UNICEF’s emergency support in Borno, Adamawa, and Yobe states directly benefitted over 1 million children (48% girls) affected by conflict. The comprehensive education service package provided in formal and non-formal settings included safe learning spaces, support for skills development across grades (foundational literacy and numeracy, psychosocial support, and vocational and life skills), teacher professional development, teaching and learning materials, and integrated data systems. In addition, reading and numeracy outcomes increased from 1% in 2020 to 24% in 2021 through the Teaching at the Right Level (TaRL) intervention. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:29/12/2021
